I"}<p>Recently I was faced with the situation where I had to use SVG icons in my web app. What did I do next? Wrapped the SVG in <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">&lt;Img&gt;</code> tag and went with it. It worked obviously, but it had its own shortcomings. This is what Iâ€™m going to discuss today.</p>

<p>Letâ€™s get started with discussing the cons of wrapping a svg in a <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">&lt;Img&gt;</code> tag:</p>

<ul>
  <li>Limited CSS based styling.</li>
  <li>In-line styling is required for some of them to work.</li>
  <li>External Stylesheets have no effect on them except for few basic modifications.</li>
</ul>

<h2 id="what-should-i-use-then">What should I use then?</h2>

<p>Letâ€™s take a look at the syntax for all of them:</p>

<ul>
  <li>Image Tag <br />
<code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">&lt;img src="./sample.svg" alt="Sample SVG" /&gt;</code></li>
  <li>Object Tag <br />
<code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">&lt;Object src="./sample.svg" alt="Sample SVG" /&gt;</code></li>
  <li>Embed Tag <br />
<code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">&lt;Embed src="./sample.svg" alt="Sample SVG"&gt;&lt;/Embed&gt;</code></li>
</ul>

